S_n(p) = \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n \dfrac1{k^p}
S(p) = \lim_{n \to \infty} S_n(p)
n \to \infty
S_{2n+1}(p) = \sum_{k=1}^{2n+1} \dfrac1{k^p} = 1 + \sum_{k=1}^n \left(\dfrac1{(2k)^p} + \dfrac1{(2k+1)^p}\right) < 1 + \sum_{k=1}^n \dfrac2{(2k)^p} = 1 + \dfrac{S_n(p)}{2^{p-1}}
S(p) \leq 1 + \dfrac{S(p)}{2^{p-1}} \implies S(p) \leq \dfrac{2^{p-1}}{2^{p-1}-1}
\begin{align} \sum_{n=1}^\infty {1\over n^2}&=1+{1\over4}+{1\over9}+{1\over16}+{1\over25}+{1\over36}+{1\over49}+{1\over64}+\cdots\cr &\lt 1+{1\over4}+{1\over4}+{1\over16}+{1\over16}+{1\over16}+{1\over16}+{1\over64}+\cdots\cr &=1+{1\over2}+{1\over4}+{1\over8}+\cdots\cr &=2\cr \end{align}
